# Submission

## Abstract (100 words)
This notebook presents a cloud-native workflow for monitoring the vegetation vigor of *Panthera onca* (Yaguareté) corridors across the Americas [1]. By fusing Sentinel-2 L2A and L1C Zarr data accessed via the EOPF STAC API, we calculate the "habitat pulse" using NDVI statistics for over 1,000 scenes [1, 2]. The methodology integrates ecological thresholds with cultural identity, utilizing distributed lazy-loading, SCL quality masking, and spatial clipping [3, 4]. Results identify habitat degradation and connectivity loss, providing a scalable tool for conservationists to track sacred soil integrity without the overhead of massive local file management [5, 6].

